   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>Dear OpenHatchers,

Back in 2010 the hip up-to-date thing to use was "jQuery tabs"
<a href="http://jqueryui.com/demos/tabs/">http://jqueryui.com/demos/tabs/</a> . It might have been outmoded; you'll
have to look into this. But if you do want to use jQuery tabs, it's
pretty easy to implement. You set up a simple HTML structure (I think
it's a &lt;ul&gt;), then call a javascript function which turns that
structure into tabs. It has lots of features all of which are
optional. One feature is "cookie persistence", i.e., the ability to
remember what tab you're on even if you leave the page.

I'm pretty sure the homepage used this solution in April 2009. Maybe
search the logs for variants of the strings "tabs" or "jquery tabs".

Happy hacking!

Raffi

2011/3/31 Asheesh Laroia &lt;<a href="mailto:bugs@openhatch.org">bugs@openhatch.org</a>&gt;:
&gt;
&gt; Asheesh Laroia &lt;<a href="mailto:asheesh@asheesh.org">asheesh@asheesh.org</a>&gt; added the comment:
&gt;
&gt; Something I think we've done in the past is make clicking each link adjust the
&gt; "fragment" (the stuff after # in <a href="http://openhatch.org/#fragment">http://openhatch.org/#fragment</a> ), and then when
&gt; you hit "Forward" and "Back", the page checks which "fragment" is active and
&gt; shows that tab. Plus I think we've been using a cookie to store which fragment
&gt; is active.
&gt;
&gt; There are probably best practices on the web for this stuff, now that it's 2011,
&gt; that I don't know the ins and outs of.
&gt;
&gt; __________________________________________
&gt; Roundup issue tracker &lt;<a href="mailto:bugs@openhatch.org">bugs@openhatch.org</a>&gt;
